				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Thanks!<br /><br />Is the internal bytes remaining counter initialized from $4013 (sample length) only when writing to $4015 (status) with the DMC bit set while the number of remaining bytes is 0? That would mean that changes to $4013 while a sample is playing have no effect on the playback, while I'm guessing that changes to the sample address while a sample is playing <em>do</em> have an effect.<br /><br />Edit: Oh, wait, just noticed that the start address and current address are separate. Is the correct version that neither writes to $4012 (sample address) nor to $4013 (sample length) while a sample is playing have any effect (other than setting up state for the next sample)?<br /><br />I wonder if the &quot;silence flag&quot; is just the enabled flag by the way. In <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.qmtpro.com/~nes/chipimages/visual2a03/nodenames.js">http://www.qmtpro.com/~nes/chipimages/v ... denames.js</a><!-- m --> you have<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">// enabled (write $4015), active (read $4015)<br />// these are actually the same register<br />pcm_en:14060,<br />pcm_on:14060,</div><br /><br />Would a model where the enabled flag is cleared whenever zero bytes remain in the sample be consistent with observed behavior? In such a model, you would have e.g. &quot;if enable bit goes from clear to set, load sample length into internal bytes remaining counter (edit: and sample start address into the internal current-address register)&quot;.</div>

