						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Edit: Oh, wait, just noticed that the start address and current address are separate. Is the correct version that neither writes to $4012 (sample address) nor to $4013 (sample length) while a sample is playing have any effect (other than setting up state for the next sample)?</div><br />See <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/Emulator_tests#APU" class="postlink">apu_test</a> 7-dmc_basics.s:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">; Delays n DMC sample bytes, assuming DMC is running at maximum rate<br />.macro delay_dmc n<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;delay 54*8 * (n)<br />.endmacro<br />&#91;...&#93;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;set_test 7,&quot;Changing $4013 shouldn't affect current sample length&quot;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;setb SNDCHN,$10&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;; start 17-byte sample<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;setb $4013,2&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; ; length of next sample = 33 bytes<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;delay_dmc 20<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;setb SNDCHN,$10&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;; start 33-byte sample<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;setb $4013,1&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; ; length of next sample = 17 bytes<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;delay_dmc 30<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;jsr should_be_playing<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;delay_dmc 6<br />&nbsp; &nbsp;jsr should_be_silent</div><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Would a model where the enabled flag is cleared whenever zero bytes remain in the sample be consistent with observed behavior? In such a model, you would have e.g. &quot;if enable bit goes from clear to set, load sample length into internal bytes remaining counter (edit: and sample start address into the internal current-address register)&quot;.</div><br />Yes. Further, the model doesn't even need a flag as state and could derive it from the counter being zero or not.<br /><br />Not sure whether you're writing an emulator, but a good way to test these questions is to implement them and run the test ROM. If you fail, the model is clearly wrong. If you pass, it might be correct. I've tried to anticipate misinterpretations of the descriptions and catch them in the tests.</div>

