				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">When a looping sample restarts, does it use the start address and length most recently written to $4012/$4013, or does it still use the start address and length that were in effect when the sample started? I'm trying to determine whether there are two or three start addresses and two or three lengths in the APU.</div><br /><br />At a high level, it works something like this:<br /><br />You have an enable flag, a start address reg and a start length reg (set directly via $4010-4013 and $4015), as well as a current address reg and a remaining bytes reg (internal regs).<br /><br />A sample is &quot;started&quot; in one of two ways: (1) by writing $4015 with the DMC enable bit set when the remaining bytes reg is 0, or (2) by the loop flag being set when the remaining bytes reg reaches 0 during playback.<br /><br />Whenever a sample is &quot;started&quot; in one of the two ways above, the internal current address and remaining bytes regs are initialized from the start address and start length regs, and sample playback starts.<br /><br />Lots of details missing of course, but the point is that there only seems to be a single set of internal regs (in Visual 2A03 as well).<br /><br />Edit: I can't get the bit counter and PCM data reg to change in Visual 2A03, even though the rdy and pcm_irq lines change as expected and a short period is used. I wonder if that's a bug...</div>

